{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527799"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14233"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14233"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.16,0.54,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107966"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6920"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14233"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90379"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12728"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15880"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45023"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107966"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old Aboriginal man presents to the General Practice clinic for a health check. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a current smoker with a 20 pack-year history. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His blood pressure is 135/85 mmHg. Recent blood tests show a total cholesterol of 5.2 mmol/L (3.9-5.5) and HDL cholesterol of 1.0 mmol/L (\u0026gt;1.0). The Australian Absolute Cardiovascular Disease Risk Calculator is used to calculate his risk of cardiovascular events in the next 5 years.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following additional investigations would provide the most useful information to further risk stratify his cardiovascular risk ?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Electrocardiogram","Exercise stress test","CT calcium score","Carotid doppler ultrasound","Echocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT calcium score\u003C/strong\u003E would provide the most useful additional information for cardiovascular risk stratification. CT calcium scoring is particularly valuable in patients with intermediate cardiovascular risk, as it can help refine risk assessment and guide management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectrocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E (ECG) is a useful tool for detecting existing heart disease, such as previous myocardial infarction or left ventricular hypertrophy. However, it does not provide information about subclinical atherosclerosis and is less sensitive for risk stratification in asymptomatic individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eexercise stress test\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to detect obstructive coronary artery disease in symptomatic patients. While it can provide information about functional capacity and exercise tolerance, it is less useful for risk stratification in asymptomatic individuals, especially those with intermediate risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid doppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can assess for carotid artery stenosis and intima-media thickness, which are markers of atherosclerosis. While this can be useful for cardiovascular risk assessment, it is less specific for coronary artery disease compared to CT calcium scoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E provides information about cardiac structure and function but does not directly assess coronary artery disease risk. It is more useful in evaluating patients with known or suspected heart disease rather than for primary prevention risk stratification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT calcium scoring quantifies the amount of calcium in the coronary arteries, which correlates with the overall burden of atherosclerosis. A score of 0 indicates very low risk, 1-100 indicates mild risk, 101-300 indicates moderate risk, and \u0026gt;300 indicates high risk. This information can be particularly valuable in patients like this Aboriginal man, who may be at higher cardiovascular risk due to ethnicity and smoking history, but whose other risk factors (blood pressure, cholesterol) are borderline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while CT calcium scoring provides valuable information, it should be used in conjunction with traditional risk factors and clinical judgment. The combination of this adjusted risk calculation and CT calcium scoring can provide an added advantage when assessment is done for this patient\u0027s cardiovascular risk and guide appropriate preventive strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT calcium scoring can provide additional information for cardiovascular risk stratification in intermediate-risk patients.","A CT calcium score of 100-300 Agatston units indicates moderate coronary artery calcification and moderately increased cardiovascular risk.","Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples have a higher risk of cardiovascular disease compared to non-Indigenous Australians."],"references":["Pylypchuk R, Wells S, Kerr A, et al. Cardiovascular disease risk prediction equations in 400 000 primary care patients in New Zealand: a derivation and validation study. Lancet 2018; 391(10133):1897-1907. doi:10.1016/s0140-6736(18)30664-0","Wells S, Riddell T, Kerr A, et al. Cohort Profile: The PREDICT Cardiovascular Disease Cohort in New Zealand Primary Care (PREDICT-CVD 19). Int J Epidemiol 2017; 46(1):22. doi:10.1093/ije/dyv312"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90379"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14233"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90379"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T12:23:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T12:24:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6920"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107966"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":n